The legislation would revoke Trump's executive order declaring an emergency so he could use other federal funding to pay for his wall.
"When you see the vote today there will be nowhere near the votes to override a veto," said House GOP Whip Steve Scalise, R-La.
Senate Democratic leader Chuck Schumer said Trump is trying to "bend the law" with his declaration of a national emergency on the southern border.
Senate voting on Trump's emergency order could drag under a rarely used procedure, which an aide said is possibly a first for the chamber.
Trump's declaration of a national emergency gives him access to about $3.6 billion in funding for military construction projects to divert to border fencing.